NHS England and NHS Improvement has a commitment to increase the role of those with a lived experience within the delivery of Health and Justice Liaison and Diversion services. Accordingly, across the West Midlands existing Liaison and Diversion Service Providers will be required from April 2021 to include Peer Support within their current delivery model.
In some case's Liaison and Diversion service providers will look to develop and deliver a peer support model themselves, others may look to third parties to sub-contract.
To support Liaison and Diversion providers in the development of peer support NHS England and NHS Improvement (Midlands) would like to provide them with a list of possible peer support providers from which they have the option to engage in discussions, should they wish.  Arden and Greater East Midlands Commissioning Support Unit (AGCSU), acting on behalf of NHS England & NHS Improvement Health and Justice (Midlands), invites expressions of interest (EOI) from suitably qualified and experienced service providers (including third sector organisations, social enterprise and other providers) who have suitable experience in delivering Peer Support within a criminal justice or healthcare context.
The areas which will be developing Peer Support include:
•	Coventry & Warwickshire;
•	Shropshire & Telford;
•	Black Country (this includes the boroughs of Sandwell, Wolverhampton, Walsall and Dudley)
•	Herefordshire;
•	Worcestershire;
Each of the Liaison and Diversion Service Providers has been allocated funding by NHS England and NHS Improvement, Health & Justice (Midlands) to include Peer Support within their operating model.
This PIN is seeking expressions of interest from interested providers who would like their details passed onto the Liaison & Diversion Service providers in these areas;
Liaison and Diversion Providers will, should they determine that their preferred option is to sub- contract this work, undertake their own arrangements to ensure a suitably qualified provider is appointed to deliver Peer Support.
If you are interested in having your contact details passed onto Liaison & Diversion Service Provider's please complete the Expression of Interest Form that is attached to this opportunity on the EU Supply portal, using the link below no later than 12pm Wednesday 16th December 2020.
https://uk.eu-supply.com/ctm/Supplier/PublicPurchase/35443/0/0?returnUrl=ctm/Supplier/publictenders&b=UK

The National Health Service Commissioning Board (which uses the operational name "NHS England") is opening the window ("Refresh 1") for bidders to join the Community Diagnostic Centres Framework and for existing Providers to expand their service offering. The NHS Commissioning Board established a framework (the "Framework Agreement") from which NHS England and other NHS bodies (Clinical Commissioning Groups ("CCGs"), NHS Trusts and NHS Foundation Trusts (each a "Contracting Authority" and together the "Contracting Authorities")) have the ability to award contracts or sub-contracts for a range of clinical services to be provided from community diagnostic centres (the "Services"). Please refer to the Specification at Document 3 of the ITT for more details of the Services. The objective of Framework Agreement (FA) is to: support the Contracting Authorities' (CAs) ability to improve population health: increase diagnostic capacity: improve productivity and efficiency of diagnostic activity, contribute to reducing health inequalities, deliver a better and more personalised diagnostic experience for patients and support integration of care. The framework is divided into a number of clinical diagnostic modalities and sub-modalities. Successful providers onto the framework will during the procurement process and potentially during the term of the framework, identify those modalities and sub-modalities which they are capable of providing in identified locations and also identify whether or not they have their own facilities from which such services could be provided from. A FA will be entered into by NHS England on behalf of all CAs with each successful Provider assessed as capable of providing such Services (or any of them) through this procurement process The end date of each Framework Agreement awarded pursuant to this "Refresh 1" procurement will be 12 December 2024 with an option to extend for a further 24 month period (the "Term")..
When awarding contracts pursuant to the framework it will be for CAs to determine which modalities or sub-modalities they wish to purchase based on local need and award will be permitted on the basis of either criteria set out in the FA or further competition among those on the FA. Contracts called off from the FA by CAs shall be based upon the NHS Standard Contract or Sub-Contract at National and Local NHS Prices and discounts may be offered. This Procurement is on behalf of the NHS, namely NHS England, all CCGs, NHS Trusts, NHS Foundation Trusts and each of their successor bodies. A list of organisations can be found at:
https://www.nhs.uk/servicedirectories/pages/nhstrustlisting.aspx; https://www.nhs.uk/ServiceDirectories/Pages/CCGListing.aspx; https://www.nhs.uk/ServiceDirectories/Pages/AreaTeamListing.aspx; https://www.nhs.uk/ServiceDirectories/Pages/SpecialHealthAuthorityListing.aspx;

